AGI - It is not true that the elderly "steal" the place to the young generations. On the contrary, they represent an opportunity for the future to build it in the intergenerational unit. Pope Francis points out in the message for the Fourth World Day of the Grandparents and the Elders. "The accusation aimed at the old to steal the future to young people is very present today everywhere. It is found, in other forms, even in the most advanced and modern societies," the Pope says. For example, "the belief that the elderly make the cost of the assistance they need on young people is now widespread, and in this way they subtract resources to the development of the country and therefore to young people. This is a distorted perception of reality.' It is "as if the survival of the elderly put the young at risk. As if to encourage young people it was necessary to neglect the elderly or even suppress them. The contrast between generations is a deception and is a poisoned fruit of the culture of confrontation".
&nbsp;
< blockquote
"To put young people against the elderly is an unacceptable manipulation: the age of life is at stake: that is, the real point of reference for the understanding and appreciation of human life in its entirety"
</blockquote
&nbsp;
"This happens when you lose the value of each and people become only a cost, in some cases too high to pay," continues Bergoglio, "What is worse is that, often, the elderly themselves end up being succumb to this mentality and come to consider themselves as a burden, wishing themselves first to step aside." On the other hand, "there are many women and men who seek their own personal realization in an existence as autonomous and unleashed by others as possible. Common memberships are in crisis and individuality is affirmed; the passage from "we" to "I" appears one of the most obvious signs of our times".
&nbsp;
In this context the family, which is "the first and most radical contestation of the idea that one can save himself, and one of the victims of this individualist culture. When we grow old, however, as the forces decline, the mirage of individualism, the illusion of not needing anyone and of being able to live without ties is revealed for what and; instead we find ourselves in need of everything, but now alone, without any help, without someone on whom we can rely". "It is a sad discovery that many do when it is too late >", the Pope concludes, "Loliness and Discard have become recurring elements in the context in which we are immersed. They have multiple roots: in some cases they are the fruit of a planned exclusion, a sort of sad "social conspiracy"; In other cases it is unfortunately a decision of its own. Other times they are still undergoing pretending that it is an autonomous choice. More and more we have lost the taste of fraternity and we struggle even to imagine something different." &nbsp;
