AGI -&nbsp;The Prosecutor of Rome investigates for personal injury in relation to the case of Mariusz Marian Sodkiewicz, a former Rai employee of 62 years died yesterday because of a pleural mesothelioma, a tumor form due to exposure to asbestos &nbsp; during its long service in the Roman headquarters of the public broadcaster. The pm Fabio Santoni has arranged&nbsp; the suspension of funerals (previously at 16.30 on Tuesday 14 May in the church of Santa Maria della Neve in Penna in Teverina, in the province of Terni) to carry out autopsy on the body of Sodkiewicz. In March, the complaint that the man had filed in Piazzale Clodio. To see his rights protected, Sodkiewicz addressed lawyer Ezio Bonanni, president of the Amianto National Observatory, who had long been committed to clarifying the presence of the 'killer silente' in state television buildings.&nbsp;
<br> Sodkiewicz was born in Lubsko, Poland, and had spent much of his work life in Rai. Starting in 2002 for twenty-two years, he had performed several tasks in different business locations, including the Press Office of the Prix Italia, the Digital Terrestre project, the Human Resources Directorate and that of Technology. In July 2023, man had begun to manifest the characteristic symptoms of pleural mesothelioma: difficulty breathing, persistent cough and chest pain. Later clinical investigations had confirmed the presence of the disease, attributing it to its exposure to asbestos.
&nbsp;
The mineral, as Mariusz himself had reported, was present in the buildings and plants of the issuer that, in the years 2010-2012 had arranged the plan of remediation, but the safety measures during the process were insufficient, and the employees, including Sodkiewicz, who had personally witnessed the reclamation activities of the asbestos during his normal working time, noticing also the deceit to dangerousness, were exposed.
&nbsp;
The man, among other things, had reported to his internal referents that the work had been carried out in the absence of adequate instruments of technical prevention and individual protection, but he had been constantly reassured that there was no risk for his health and that the limits of exposure to asbestos fibres had not been exceeded. Only a few days ago in the audition in commission Vigilanza RAI, the CEO Roberto Sergio, speaking on the question regarding the sending of the state of service to Franco Di Mare, had found that on the asbestos problem he had sent a "documentation that attests that in Viale Mazzini there is no risk at this time of contamination". "Mariusz Marian Sodkiewicz was part of a generation of employees who dedicated their lives to public service" &nbsp;&nbsp;- said Bonanni, who stressed: "his death, which also raises questions about safety at work and the responsibility of the institutions, is one of the many and painful testimonies of the devastating consequences of exposure to asbestos at the workplace" .<br> &nbsp;
