AGI - Get detailed images of the structure and level of fracture of the rocks of the caldera of the Flegrei Fields through the analysis of the variation in the time of the velocity of the seismic waves. At the same time, investigate the main features of the volcanic power system and the main changes between unrest or ongoing bradisism and the phenomenon occurred between 1982 and 1984. These are the goals of the study "Tracking transient changes in the plumbing system at Campi Flegrei Caldera" conducted by a multidisciplinary team of researchers from the National Institute of Geophysics and Vulcanology (INGV) and the University of Milan-Bicocca, just published on Earth and Planetary Science Letters of Elsevier. It is the first study of seismic tomography that integrates the microsystems that occurred in the Flegrei Fields over forty years, from 1982 to 2022. The researchers used a technique based on a non-linear probability approach to the resolution of the tomographic problem, analyzing the ratio between the velocity of the so-called P waves (press or pressure) and their relationship with the so-called S waves (second or cutting). This innovative method has made it possible to shed light on the characteristics of crustal velocity up to the depth of 6 km, where traditional linearized techniques have always shown limits of resolution. The use of this method, moreover, has allowed to identify for the first time three main zones of accumulation of magmatic material under the resonance area, corresponding to the sources of bradysmic deformations. While the central tanks, located at 2.5 and 3.5 km deep, reveal a prevalent accumulation of overpressure fluids, the deepest reservoir, located at 5 km, shows consistent speed values with a magma accumulation. Important innovative element of the method studied is the possibility of identifying the main variations in the time of velocity anomalies, and, therefore, of the evolution of the accumulation zones of magmatic material. This was possible thanks to the intuition of the team of researchers who developed in a pioneering way the method of seismic tomography in 4 dimensions (space and time). The results show that the two episodes analyzed of unrest of 1982-1984 and from 2005 to 2022, although involving different volumes, were both characterized by episodes of lifts and accumulation in the central area predominantly of magmatic gases in overpressure and deep magma, suggesting that both of these processes play an important role in in in in inducing the caldera unrest. This approach can prove to be a useful tool to monitor over time the evolution of the magmatic system of the caldera and the will of the researchers is to extend as soon as possible the probability model even to the years after 2022.
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
